      • createNonNullableWithInitialValue

        IBeforeUpgradeColumn createNonNullableWithInitialValue(java.lang.Object initialValue)
        Throws if:
        • Column already exists.
      • Column doesn't exist and doesn't have an associated property (we don't know the type).
    • Column is nullable.
If column doesn't exist and has an associated property, it will create the column for that property as a non-nullable column with the given initial value.

In general, the initial value should be an illegal value. Subsequent update(s) will then populate the column with legal values. An illegal value makes it easier to track down the origin of the value.

Care must be taken to ensure the subsequent update(s) cover all cases. We recommend the use of this method over create() for non-nullable columns as this obviates the need to make the new column non-nullable later.

Returns:
this

  • createNullableWithInitialValue

    IBeforeUpgradeColumn createNullableWithInitialValue(java.lang.Object initialValue)
    Throws if:
    • Column already exists.
    • Column is non-nullable.
    If column doesn't exist, it will create the column for that property as a nullable column with the given value.

    On Oracle, used to add a nullable column with an initial value when improved performance is required. Note that if the column is added is for a subtype (not a root type), non-subtype rows will end up with the initial value. If not Oracle, there is no performance optimization, and initial values are only added to appropriate subtypes.

    Returns:
    this
